                  </Label>
                  <Label layoutX="39.0" layoutY="266.0" prefHeight="32.0" prefWidth="555.0" text="Why is it protecting biometric data important?">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Eras Medium ITC" size="27.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Label>
                  <TextArea editable="false" layoutX="84.0" layoutY="70.0" prefHeight="195.0" prefWidth="477.0" style="-fx-background-color: white;" text="Biometric Data is personally identifiable information, or PII, which means any data &#10;that could potentially be used to identify a particular person. In other words, &#10;biometrics are biological measurements or physical characteristics that can be used &#10;to identify individuals. Examples include fingerprint mapping, facial recognition etc. &#10;Biometric data are unique and permanent PII. When data is obtained from a person, &#10;and it is linked with their date of birth, weight, religion, or financial information it &#10;becomes PII. Then this biometric data is stored in the database and is used for &#10;authorization, identification and other security purposes. As a little fun fact, the word&#10;'biometric' stems from the greek words bio (“life”) and metric (“measurement”)." />
                  <TextArea editable="false" layoutX="78.0" layoutY="323.0" prefHeight="158.0" prefWidth="477.0" style="-fx-background-color: white;" text="Biometric data contains information that is unique to everyone. &#10;As a result, people should be informed if their personal information is collected. &#10;Otherwise, if a data breach occurs and their biometric data is leaked, the people &#10;would not even know that their personal information is out there in the public. &#10;They should also be aware of the reason their data is being collected. Because &#10;sometimes the data collected is cross-matched, meaning biometric trait that is &#10;collected for one purpose but is used for a different purpose without the person’s &#10;knowledge and consent." />
