                  </Label>
                  <TextArea editable="false" layoutX="24.0" layoutY="124.0" prefHeight="419.0" prefWidth="637.0" style="-fx-background-color: white;" text="Suprema is the security company responsible for the Bio-star 2 biometrics lock system which enables centralized &#10;control for access to secure facilities like warehouses or office buildings. It makes use of fingerprints and facial &#10;recognition for identification which is used by almost 5700 organizations in 87 countries including the UK &#10;metropolitan police. The UK Metropolitan police, defence contractors, and banks found that the fingerprints, facial &#10;recognition, encrypted usernames and passwords, and personal information of employees were made publicly &#10;available. The Israeli security researchers, Noam Rotem and Ran Locar were running a side project to find flaws in &#10;companies’ systems that could potentially lead to data breaches. According to their research, Biostar 2’s database &#10;was unprotected and unencrypted. Locar and Rotem had access to over 27.8m records, and 23 gigabytes worth of &#10;data including admin panels, dashboards, fingerprint data, facial recognition data, face photos of users, unencrypted&#10; usernames and passwords, logs of facility access, security levels and clearance, and personal details of staff. &#10;Rotem told Guardian that they were able to find the plain-text passwords of administrator accounts and also change &#10;data and add new users. The researchers were able to access data from co-working organizations in the US and&#10; Indonesia, a gym chain in India and Sri Lanka, a medicine supplied in the United Kingdom, and a car parking space &#10;developer in Finland. The researchers also mentioned that the scale of the breach was alarming because, unlike &#10;passwords, fingerprints cannot be changed. “Instead of saving a hash of the fingerprint (that can’t be &#10;reverse-engineered) they are saving people’s actual fingerprints that can be copied for malicious purposes,” the &#10;researchers said in the paper. They reached out to Suprema before taking the paper to the Guardian, but the &#10;security firm did not reply. The head of marketing, Andy Ahn, told the Guardian that there is an in-depth evaluation &#10;going on and they will inform customers if there was a threat. He said,” If there has been any definite threat on our &#10;products and/or services, we will take immediate actions and make appropriate announcements to protect our &#10;customers’ valuable businesses and assets”.  The biometric lock system is nothing but a threat to an individual &#10;without security which was the main concern for Suprema Company. It can leak biometric data which may have &#10;been used in banks, etc. by a user. Therefore, such leaks might be a huge problem around the globe." />
