      <Tab text="Privacy of biometric data">
        <content>
          <AnchorPane minHeight="0.0" minWidth="0.0" prefHeight="180.0" prefWidth="200.0" style="-fx-background-color: white;">
               <children>
                  <Label layoutX="123.0" layoutY="35.0" text="How private should biometric data really be?">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Eras Medium ITC" size="22.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Label>
                  <Label layoutX="79.0" layoutY="345.0" text="Is it easy or even possible to forge biometric data?">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Eras Medium ITC" size="22.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Label>
                  <TextArea editable="false" layoutX="43.0" layoutY="84.0" prefHeight="239.0" prefWidth="595.0" style="-fx-background-color: white;" text="Government, law enforcement, and business will all employ biometric technology more and more &#10;over the course of the next ten years; according to industry observers, the possibilities are endless &#10;Biometrics can be used in any circumstance that permits a human-machine interface, it will be &#10;necessary to have strict legal, administrative, and technical measures in place to make sure that &#10;biometrics don't compromise the privacy of personal data. The way the systems are built, and the &#10;data is handled will ultimately determine whether biometrics is a friend or a foe of privacy. &#10;Technology may even improve privacy if it is created with that goal in mind. The data protection &#10;community rejecting biometrics, in general, would be, at best, short-sighted. Applications used by &#10;governments, law enforcement, and businesses are expanding globally. Since biometric technology &#10;must &quot;conform to the rules and expectations of a privacy-minded society,&quot; the data protection&#10; community must take immediate action to make sure that public and private sector organizations &#10;contemplating it understand this.">
                     <font>
                        <Font size="13.0" />
                     </font>
                  </TextArea>
                  <TextArea editable="false" layoutX="43.0" layoutY="386.0" prefHeight="163.0" prefWidth="583.0" style="-fx-background-color: white;" text="Yes, there are several techniques to hack biometrics. The term &quot;hacking&quot; refers to a variety of &#10;activities, but in this context, it is most used to describe the capacity to evade biometric &#10;verification in some way. For instance, one can trick biometric security measures using:&#10;&#10;Generating biometrics with deep fake technologies utilizing a fake or synthetic identity to pass &#10;security checks, discovering a way to get around the biometrics check by obtaining someone's &#10;biometrics from databases, reproducing someone's biometrics, or social engineering (by &#10;convincing the victim to authorize them).">
                     <font>
                        <Font size="13.0" />
                     </font>
                  </TextArea>
